Q.What are Spring Profiles?

Spring Profiles allow you to define different configurations for different environments
(like development, testing, production) within the same application codebase. This helps you
avoid hardcoding environment-specific values and makes your application more flexible and
maintainable.

Why use profiles?

You can have different beans, properties, or configurations for each environment.
You avoid manual changes when moving your app from dev to prod.
2. Environment-Specific Configurations
You can create beans or configuration files that are only loaded for a specific environment.

Example:
Suppose you have two different data sources: one for development and one for production.


@Configuration
public class DataSourceConfig {

    @Bean
    @Profile("dev")
    public DataSource devDataSource() {
        // return a datasource for development
    }

    @Bean
    @Profile("prod")
    public DataSource prodDataSource() {
        // return a datasource for production
    }
}

Only the bean matching the active profile will be created.

3. Activating Profiles
You can activate a profile in several ways:

a. Using application.properties or application.yml
properties

spring.profiles.active=dev

or

yaml

spring:
  profiles:
    active: dev
b. Using Command Line
bash


java -jar myapp.jar --spring.profiles.active=prod
c. Using Environment Variables
bash


export SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE=prod
d. Programmatically
java


ConfigurableApplicationContext ctx = new SpringApplicationBuilder(MyApp.class)
    .profiles("dev")
    .run(args);
4. Using the @Profile Annotation for Beans
The @Profile annotation is used to indicate that a bean is only loaded for a specific profile.
You can use it on classes or methods.
Example on a class:

@Service
@Profile("test")
public class TestEmailService implements EmailService {
    // Only loaded when 'test' profile is active
}

Example on a method:

@Bean
@Profile("prod")
public EmailService prodEmailService() {
    return new SmtpEmailService();
}
5. Profile-Specific Properties Files
You can also have different property files for each profile:

application-dev.properties
application-prod.properties

Spring will automatically load the file matching the active profile.

Example: If spring.profiles.active=dev, then application-dev.properties is loaded in addition
to application.properties.

